            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Wei Li\u2019s life is steeped in the aromas of oolong and jasmine, a scent map of his native San Francisco Chinatown. Born to parents who immigrated from Guangdong in the late 1960s, Wei grew up in a cramped apartment just off Portsmouth Square. His childhood was a symphony of clacking mahjong tiles and the sizzle of woks from the restaurants below. His parents ran a small grocery, instilling in him a relentless work ethic and a deep-seated sense of duty to family and community.\n\nWhile his parents hoped he\u2019d pursue a more prestigious career, Wei was a pragmatist. After graduating from Galileo High, he enrolled at City College of San Francisco, earning an Associate's degree in Business Administration. The degree felt practical, a tool he could use to help his family, not a ticket to leave them. During college, he started working part-time at the Grant Avenue Tea Co., a venerable shop owned by the elderly Mr. Chen. Wei was a natural, possessing a quiet patience and a genuine curiosity for the histories behind each tea leaf.\n\nA major turning point came when Wei was 32. Mr. Chen, with no children to inherit the business, decided to retire. Seeing Wei\u2019s dedication, he offered to sell him the shop on a payment plan. Wei used his modest savings and took a significant loan, pouring everything into preserving the institution. This commitment, however, contributed to the end of his marriage; his ex-wife yearned for a house in the East Bay, a life he couldn't and wouldn't embrace.\n\nNow 47, Wei is the quintessential neighborhood fixture. His life is a comforting routine. He wakes in his small, rent-controlled apartment, walks the half-dozen blocks to his shop, greeting other merchants along the way. His day is spent advising tourists on the nuances of pu-erh and sharing neighborhood gossip with lifelong customers. He is the quiet center of his small world, a living link to Chinatown\u2019s past. His dream isn't of expansion or wealth, but of stewardship: to ensure the Grant Avenue Tea Co. remains an authentic sanctuary, a place of peace and tradition, for the next generation. He secretly hopes a younger kid from the neighborhood will one day walk in, just as he did, looking for a job and finding a calling."
