            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, his hands too small for the heavy mahjong tiles. His father, smelling of dried fish and fatigue, wasn\u2019t teaching him the game, but how to build the wall. \"Steady hands, Wei,\" he\u2019d said in their dialect. Each cool, inscribed tile clicking into place felt like a secret passed down. It wasn't about winning, but about building something solid together. That quiet lesson in patience and structure became the foundation of his life.\n\n2.\nHe was 20, still new at the shop. Mr. Chen slid a small, precious tin across the counter. \"Da Hong Pao,\" the old man whispered. \"You brew.\" Wei\u2019s hands trembled as he measured the dark, twisted leaves. The earthy aroma filled his lungs, quieting his racing heart. In that moment of intense focus, pouring the water just so, he felt he wasn\u2019t just serving a customer; he was honoring a history. That reverence never left him.\n\n3.\nThe night Mr. Chen offered him the shop, Wei, then 32, didn\u2019t go home. He walked to Portsmouth Square and sat on a bench, the weight of the loan pressing down on him. He watched the grandmothers doing their late-night exercises and heard the familiar clang of a distant kitchen. He wasn't just buying a business; he was accepting a responsibility. The fear was immense, but the feeling of belonging was stronger. He chose this place.\n\n4.\nHe was 34. The final conversation with his wife wasn't a fight, but a quiet statement of facts. \"A yard, Wei. In Concord,\" she\u2019d said, her voice full of a dream he couldn't share. He looked out their window at the neon glow of Grant Avenue and could almost smell the tea from his shop. He loved her, but he realized his roots were planted too deep in this concrete to ever flourish in suburban soil. It was a silent, heartbreaking choice.\n\n5.\nJust last year, a quiet high school kid from the neighborhood, maybe 16, came in. He didn't just ask for boba; he pointed to the pu-erh cakes. \"How do they get old like that?\" he asked, genuinely curious. Wei spent twenty minutes explaining the aging process, seeing the same spark in the boy's eyes that he once felt himself. For the first time, his quiet hope for a successor felt less like a dream and more like a future waiting to steep."
